You don&#x27;t really even need a stream cipher, just random data if you&#x27;re using XOR. You&#x27;re right that XOR is trivially commutative, but it is weak to known-plaintext attacks which makes it unsuitable for this algorithm.<p>Suppose you have a deck { 1, 2, 3, 4 }, I&#x27;m alice(A) and you&#x27;re bob(B) and I&#x27;ll denote xor with dot. I shuffle it with the first round, revealing<p><pre><code>    { A(3), A(1), A(2), A(4) }
</code></pre>
and then you shuffle revealing<p><pre><code>    { B.A(2), B.A(4), B.A(3), B.A(1) }
</code></pre>
Then we re-encrypt with unique keys:<p><pre><code>    { A_1.B(2), A_2.B(4), A_3.B(3), A_4.B(1) }

    { A_1.B_1(2), A_2.B_2(4), A_3.B_3(3), A_4.B_4(1) }
</code></pre>
Now you &quot;deal&quot; me the first card by revealing B_1. This means that I know that the first slot is card 2. But I also know `B xor A xor 2` from the end of the first phase, which means it&#x27;s easy to calculate what `B xor A` is. From this, I can decrypt the entire deck.
